{"title_page": "Copper Sun", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox book\n<!-- |italic title = (see above) -->\n| name             = Copper Sun\n| image            = Copper Sun book cover.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Official cover art\n| alt              = \n| author           = [[Sharon M. Draper]]\n| title_orig       = \n| translator       = \n| illustrator      = \n| cover_artist     = \n| country          = United States\n| language         = \n| series           = \n| subject          = \n| genre            = Historical fiction\n| publisher        = [[Atheneum Books]]\n| publisher2       = \n| pub_date         = 2006\n| awards           = [[Coretta Scott King Award]]\n| isbn             = 9781416953487\n}}\n\n'''''Copper Sun''''' is a 2006  [[young adult (psychology)|young adult]] novel by [[Coretta Scott King Award]]-winning author [[Sharon Draper]]. It was a [[National Book Award]] winner.\n\n== Characters ==\n* '''Amari''' is a strong 15-year-old slave, and the main character who endures the horrors of slavery.\n*'''Polly''' is a 15-year-old indentured servant that changes her mind about slavery when she meets Amari and sees how they are treated.\n*'''Mrs. Derby''' is a sweet, affectionate woman and Mr. Derby's 18 year old, second wife. She gets pregnant by Noah, a slave and her bodyguard whom she loves,  and Mr. Derby gets so enraged by his wife having a black baby, that he kills Noah and the baby.\n* '''Nathan''' is a kind young man who helps the children along their journey.\n* '''Noah''' is a caring, strong young man who is in love with Mrs.Derby, and impregnates Mrs. Derby. He is her bodyguard.\n*'''Besa''' \"Buck\" is a drummer from Amari's village and her fiance who becomes enslaved after the capture.\n*'''Clay''' is Mr. Derby's son who impregnates Amari. He is left tied to a tree by the children as a rattlesnake is slithering toward him.\n*'''Mr. Derby''' is the harsh and cruel slave owner who kills Mrs. Derby's baby and Noah.\n*'''Kwasi''' is Amari's precocious little brother who dies shortly after the massacre by getting impaled in the stomach near the village\n* '''Komla''' Amari and Kwasi's father is the village storyteller who was murdered during the capture.\n*'''Tidbit''' is an overly imaginative child. He is also the son of Teenie. He loves Hushpuppy, his dog, very much, and hates the thought of parting with him.\n*'''Afi''' is Amari's good friend who is like a motherly figure to Amari from the boat to the new land.\n*'''Teenie''' is Tidbits mother. She was born into slavery. She is the head chef at Derbyshire farms. She helps Amari settle in and gives Amari and Polly jobs to help around the kitchen\n\n== Setting ==\nThe beginning of the book is set in Ziavi which is the African village that Amari and Besa have grown up in. Then they are taken away to Cape Coast Castle and are loaded onto the slave ships to America. They are then sold and Amari goes to Charlestown, South Carolina. In the end, they make it to Fort Mose, Florida.\nThe time period for this book is around the 1700s.\n\n== Background ==\nWhen Draper traveled to [[Ghana]], West Africa, she visited the Point of No Return and the castles had thousands of slaves that were kept before getting on the ship which made her inspired to write this novel.<ref>{{cite web| last =| first =  | authorlink = sharon draper | coauthors = | title =Copper Sun - My Spirit Speaks | work = | publisher =Sharon Draper | url = http://sharondraper.com/bookdetail.asp?id=20 | website =www.sharondraper.com | accessdate = 18 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Major Themes ==\n''Copper Sun'' addresses issues of the African Slave Trade, slavery in America, and freedom.<ref>{{cite web\n | last = \n| first =\n | authorlink = Scholastic Corporation\n| coauthors =\n | title = Copper Sun\n | work =\n | publisher = Scholastic\n | date = \n| url = http://www.scholastic.com/teachers/book/copper-sun\n | format = \n | doi = \n | accessdate = 2012-03-15}}</ref> Beverly Almond noted that the novel expresses \u201cunimaginable hardship\u201d and \u201cstarvation and disease\u201d.<ref>{{cite journal\n | last = Almond\n| first = Beverly\n| authorlink = \n| coauthors = \n | title = Copper Sun\n| journal = School Library Journal\n | volume = \n| issue = 4\n | pages = 1\n | publisher = School Library Journal\n | location = \n| date = April 2007\n | url = http://web.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail?sid=c330893f-d70a-4282-8631-6f071ff654eb%40sessionmgr13&vid=1&hid=9&bdata=JkF1dGhUeXBlPWlwLGN1c3R1aWQmY3VzdGlkPXM4NDU1ODYxJnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ%3d%3d#db=mat&AN=24703061\n | jstor =\n | issn = 0362-8930\n | doi =\n | id =\n | mr =\n | zbl =\n | jfm =\n | accessdate = 2012-03-15 }}</ref> Another critic claimed that the book showed themes of \"pain, hope, and determination\" and \"human exploitation and suffering\".<ref>{{cite journal\n | last = Larson\n| first = Gerry\n| authorlink = \n| coauthors =\n | title = Copper Sun.\n| journal = School Library Journal\n | volume = 52\n| issue = 1\n | pages = 1\n | publisher = School Library Journey\n | location = \n| date = January 2006\n | url = http://web.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail?vid=3&hid=13&sid=c02625b4-c737-4aa6-9ea4-8e9a9a616208%40sessionmgr13&bdata=JkF1dGhUeXBlPWlwLGN1c3R1aWQmY3VzdGlkPXM4NDU1ODYxJnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ%3d%3d#db=lkh&AN=19484353\n | jstor =\n | issn =0362-8930\n | doi =\n | id =\n | mr =\n | zbl =\n | jfm =}}</ref> Kirkus Reviews added the novel showed \"cynicism and realistic outlook\".<ref>{{cite journal\n | last = \n| first = \n| authorlink = Kirkus Reviews\n| coauthors =\n | title = Copper Sun.\n| journal = Kirkus Reviews\n | volume = 74\n| issue = 1\n | pages = 1\n | publisher =\n | location =  Kircus Reviews\n| date = January 1, 2006\n | url = http://web.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail?vid=3&hid=13&sid=c02625b4-c737-4aa6-9ea4-8e9a9a616208%40sessionmgr13&bdata=JkF1dGhUeXBlPWlwLGN1c3R1aWQmY3VzdGlkPXM4NDU1ODYxJnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ%3d%3d#db=lkh&AN=19481182\n | jstor =\n | issn = 1948-7428\n | doi =\n | id =\n | mr =\n | zbl =\n | jfm =\n | accessdate = 2012-03-13}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nMost critics saw ''Copper Sun'' as \u201cunflinching and unforgettable\u201d.<ref>{{cite web\n | last = \n| first =\n | authorlink = Scholastic Corporation\n| coauthors =\n | title = Copper Sun\n | work =\n | publisher = Scholastic\n | date = \n| url = http://www.scholastic.com/teachers/book/copper-sun\n | format = \n | doi = \n | accessdate = 2012-03-15}}</ref> Another critic thought of the novel as \u201ccharacter driven, with a fast moving plot, and unforgettable characters\u201d.<ref>{{cite web\n | last = \n| first =\n | authorlink = sharon draper \n| coauthors =\n | title =sharondraper.com\n | work =\n | publisher = \n | date = \n| url = http://sharondraper.com/index.asp\n | format =\n | doi =\n | accessdate = 2012-03-15}}</ref> Agreeing, another critic noted that the novel was \"horrific\" \"multi-faceted\" and that \"[they were] afraid to turn the page\"<ref>{{cite journal\n | last = Cuseo\n| first = Allan O'Grady\n| authorlink = \n| coauthors =\n | title = Copper Sun.\n| journal = Catholic Library World\n | volume = 77\n| issue = 1\n | pages = 1\n | publisher = Catholic Library World \n | location = \n| date = September 2006\n | url = http://web.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail?vid=4&hid=17&sid=82fb6b68-ddf2-4346-98d0-c3012259785d%40sessionmgr12&bdata=JkF1dGhUeXBlPWlwLGN1c3R1aWQmY3VzdGlkPXM4NDU1ODYxJnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ%3d%3d\n | jstor =\n | issn = 0008-820X\n | doi =\n | id =\n | mr =\n | zbl =\n | jfm =\n | accessdate = 2012-03-18 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nSharon Draper's ''Copper Sun'' won the Coretta Scott King award in 2007.<ref>{{cite web\n | title = Coretta Scott King Book Awards - All Recipients, 1970-Present\n | publisher =American Library Association \n | location = | date =\n | language = \n | url =http://www.ala.org/emiert/coretta-scott-king-book-awards-all-recipients-1970-present\n | accessdate = 18 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography =